TIME AND SPACE COMPLEXITY 

=algorithm analysis
programmers write algo and codes but it is not necessary that the designed code is the most optimal
the algo need to be judged so that we will more harder to get more efficient algo
for this we do algorithm analysis which means process of evaluating the efficiency of an algo in terms of:
execution time
memory usage
scalability for large input sizes
it helps developers determine which algo performs better for large data


=why algorithm analysis is important
Performance Optimization
Helps choose the fastest algorithm.

Scalability
Determines how the program behaves when data size increases.

Efficient Resource Usage
Reduces CPU usage and memory consumption.

Real-World Applications
Used in search engines, navigation systems, social media, etc.



=for example algo a checks elements one by one and algo b uses binary search
for one million elements
linear search  1000000
binary search  approx 20 
so you see the difference, interesting right 
so when you optimized you algo which runs through millions of data then you save you cpu usage, monitor screen time, your time, electricity, produce less heat delays destruction of nature, your bill and ultimately makes everyone happy.


=TIME COMPLEXITY
it measures how the running time of an algorithm grows with input size(n) rather than the actual time taken on a machine to execute it.
it represents the numbers of operations executed
it does not depends on cpu speed, programming language, compiler optimization
it depends on algorithm design, input size
represents via T(n)=numbers of steps required
TYPES
best case = minimum time required by an algorithm
worst case = the maximum time required by an algo
average case = expected time taken for all possible inputs


=Big-O notation
it represents the upper bound of an algorithm running time
it describes how runtime grows as input size increases
if the runtime grows proportional to n^2 then O(n^2)
if the runtime grows proportional to n then O(n)
and if T(n)=5n^2+2n+10 then O(n^2)
Big-O ignores:
constants
lower order terms

example
T(n)=10n+50
complexity becomes O(n)

other asymptotic notations used in algorithm analysis:
Big-Omega Ω → represents lower bound (best case)


=common time complexity types
complexity        notation      meaning
constant          O(1)          execution time does not depend on input size
logarithmic       O(log n)      problem size reduces by half each step
linear            O(n)          runtime increases directly proportional to input size
linearithmic      O(nlogn)      used in efficient sorting algo
quadratic         O(n^2)        nested loops
cubic             O(n^3)        three nested loops
exponential       O(2^n)        recursive fibonnaci without optimization
factorial         O(n!)         generating all permutation



=SPACE COMPLEXITY
measures how much memory an algorithm requires as input size increases
it includes:
input space
auxiliary space(extra space)

input space
memory required to store input data

auxiliary space
extra memory used by algorithm apart from input data

example
merge sort uses extra array so auxiliary space = O(n)

bubble sort does not use extra memory so auxiliary space = O(1)

=components of space complexity
memory that does not depends on input size = fixed part
program instruction
variables
constant

memory depending on input size = variable part
arrays
dynamic objects
recursive stack

example
factorial using recursion uses stack memory for each recursive call so space complexity becomes O(n)

another example
iterative factorial uses only variables so space complexity becomes O(1)

=TIME AND SPACE TRADE OFF
sometimes faster algorithms use more memory
sometimes memory efficient algorithms are slower

example
merge sort
time complexity = O(n log n)
space complexity = O(n)

bubble sort
time complexity = O(n^2)
space complexity = O(1)

developers choose algorithm depending on system requirements

=real world importance
used in large scale systems like
google search engine
facebook feed ranking
amazon product recommendation
navigation systems like google maps
database indexing systems

IN INTERVIEW ALWAYS AIM FOR O(LOG N), O(N), O(N LOG N)

avoid O(N^2), O(2^N), O(N!) for large datasets whenever possible










